1)what is interceptor and filters?
Filter
A Filter is used to intercept HTTP requests and responses before they reach the servlet or controller.
It is part of the Servlet API and works at the web container level.
Filters are mainly used for:
logging
authentication
request validation
response modification
compression

Interceptor
An Interceptor is a Spring-specific feature used to intercept requests before and after controller execution.
It works at the Spring MVC level.
Interceptors are mainly used for:
authentication
authorization
logging
performance monitoring
pre/post processing

2)How we can create Asynchronous REST APIs
Asynchronous REST APIs are used when a request takes more time to process, and we do not want the client thread to wait until completion.
In Spring Boot, we can create async APIs using @Async and CompletableFuture.
First, enable async support using @EnableAsync in the main class.
Then create a service method with @Async, which runs in a separate thread.
The controller returns CompletableFuture instead of direct response.
This improves performance and scalability because the server can handle multiple requests concurrently.
Async APIs are commonly used for email sending, file processing, report generation, and external API calls.

ex:-
@SpringBootApplication
@EnableAsync
public class App {
}

@Service
public class UserService {

    @Async
    public CompletableFuture<String> getData() {

        return CompletableFuture.completedFuture("Success");
    }
}

@RestController
public class UserController {

    @Autowired
    UserService service;

    @GetMapping("/test")
    public CompletableFuture<String> test() {

        return service.getData();
    }
}

3) How we can execute rest API's without token?
In Spring Boot, we can allow specific REST APIs to execute without a token by configuring Spring Security to make those endpoints public.
Using permitAll(), we can bypass authentication for selected APIs like login, signup, or health-check endpoints.
All other APIs can still remain secured with JWT or other authentication mechanisms.
This configuration is usually done inside the Spring Security configuration class.
Public APIs are commonly used for authentication, registration, Swagger docs, and monitoring endpoints.

We can allow APIs without token using permitAll(), WebSecurityCustomizer, or custom JWT filter logic.
permitAll() allows access but still passes through security filters.
web.ignoring() completely skips Spring Security processing.
We can also manually bypass token validation inside custom JWT filters.
In microservices, API Gateway can control which APIs require authentication

4)how we can manage transactions in spring boot?
In Spring Boot, transactions are mainly managed using the @Transactional annotation.
It ensures that all database operations inside a method execute as a single unit of work.
If all operations are successful, the transaction is committed; if any exception occurs, the transaction is rolled back automatically.
Spring internally uses AOP and Transaction Manager to handle transaction management.
We usually place @Transactional at the service layer because business logic is handled there.
Spring Boot supports both declarative transaction management (@Transactional) and programmatic transaction management.
Transactions help maintain data consistency and integrity in applications.

==>Declarative Transaction Management
Declarative transaction management means Spring automatically manages transactions using the @Transactional annotation.
Developer only declares transaction rules, and Spring handles:
transaction begin
commit
rollback

Example:
@Transactional
public void transferMoney() {

    debit();
    credit();
}
How it Works
Spring creates a proxy object using AOP
Before method execution → transaction starts
If method executes successfully → commit happens
If exception occurs → rollback happens automatically

This is the most commonly used approach because it reduces boilerplate code.

==>Programmatic Transaction Management
In programmatic transaction management, developer manually controls transactions using TransactionManager or TransactionTemplate.

Example:
@Autowired
PlatformTransactionManager manager;
public void test() {

    TransactionStatus status =
            manager.getTransaction(new DefaultTransactionDefinition());

    try {

        // DB operations

        manager.commit(status);

    } catch (Exception e) {

        manager.rollback(status);
    }
}
How it Works
Developer manually starts transaction
Explicitly commits or rolls back transaction
Gives more control over transaction flow